Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: Current approaches to hierarchical text classification often rely on auxiliary graph encoders or complex fusion mechanisms to integrate label hierarchies into semantic representations—especially when leveraging pre-trained language models (PLMs). While effective, these methods introduce architectural complexity and may decouple hierarchy modeling from the natural semantics captured by PLMs. Recent work (e.g., RLHR, HiAGM, HyperIM) demonstrates the importance of global hierarchy awareness but still require dedicated modules for structure encoding, limiting end-to-end compatibility with standard PLMs. My key insight is that *label hierarchies can be encoded directly into the lexical space of PLMs through carefully designed label names*, a process I term "hierarchy-informed lexicalization." Instead of using external graph networks or hyperbolic embeddings, we can inject hierarchical knowledge into labels by augmenting their surface forms with structural context—such as ancestor paths or depth-aware tokens—so that the PLM inherently learns both semantic meaning and hierarchical position during embedding lookup. This approach leverages the PLM’s existing capacity to understand compositional language, eliminating the need for separate hierarchy encoders. Unlike prior work, this method operates entirely within the standard PLM framework, enabling seamless integration with frozen or fine-tuned models while preserving logical consistency across levels. The novelty lies in treating hierarchy not as an external graph but as *implicit linguistic structure* that can be surfaced through controlled lexical design. By doing so, we maintain full compatibility with entailment-based or similarity-based classification paradigms used in zero-shot and few-shot settings, where parameter efficiency and generalization are critical.

